'''Troy Yocum''' (born June 25, 1979) is a veteran of the [[Iraq war]], who  hiked over seven thousand miles across America in 2010-2011 to help bring awareness to issues faced by veterans and their families.

==Drum hike==
Inspired by his [[World War II]] grandfather, who took his own life, and a close military friend, who lost his home after returning from deployment, Yocum decided to make it his personal mission to help struggling veterans.<ref name="army.mil">{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mil/article/39302/iraq-vet-hiking-across-nation-to-raise-5-million/|title=Iraq vet hiking across nation to raise $5 million|author=John Crosby|publisher=Army.mil|date=18 May 2010|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/WNT/video/conversation-hiking-america-11861294|title=The Conversation: Hiking Across America |date=12 October 2010|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref> He began a 16-month journey, dubbed "The Drum Hike" on April 17, 2010 at the [[Kentucky Derby]]'s "Thunder Over Louisville" celebration.  Yocum bangs his drum when entering towns and cities to bring attention to his cause and carries a bat for mayors and governors to sign.<ref name="soldangels">{{cite web|url=http://www.soldiersangels.org/drumhike.html|publisher=Soldiers Angels|title=Drum Hike for Our Heroes|accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> Averaging 20 miles per day, the hike will take him, his wife, and two dogs over more than seven thousand miles<ref name="examiner">{{cite news|title='Hike for our Heroes' coming to Ohio and how we and Mayor Berger can help|author=Lori Friend|date=10 May 2011|accessdate=28 May 2011|publisher=Examiner}}</ref> and 37 major U.S. cities by the time they make it home.<ref name="armymomstrong">{{cite web|url=http://armymomstrong.com/tag/troy-yocum/|title=A Soldier<U+2019>s Hike for Our Heroes|author=Army Mom|date=15 February 2010|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>  Troy's goal is to raise five million dollars and was sponsored by nonprofit [[Soldiers' Angels]].<ref name="soldangels" /><ref name="blog.tonic">{{cite web|url=http://blog.tonic.com/iraq-vet-drums-across-us-to-help-military-families/|title=Iraq Vet Drums Across US To Help Military Families|date=5 May 2010|author=Katherine Gustafson|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref> Due to the extreme physical activity, he has suffered several different medical complications. While in [[Colorado]], he suffered an attack of kidney stones, which required hospitalization<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/military/2010-11-21-veterans-walk-charity_N.htm?csp=34news&utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=feed&utm_campaign=Feed:+UsatodaycomNation-TopStories+%28News+-+Nation+-+Top+Stories%29&utm_content=Twitter|title=Ex-soldier walks nation for military families|author=Kate McGinty|publisher=The Desert Sun, USA Today|date=21 November 2010|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref> and in January 2011, Yocum's foot became infected and hence slowed the hike.<ref name="kxan">{{cite news|url=http://www.kxan.com/dpp/military/troy-yocum-limps-into-san-marcos|title=Troy Yocum limps into San Marcos|date=29 January 2011|author=Jacqueline Ingles|publisher=KXAN|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>  In January 2011, Soldier's Angels pulled their support for Yocum due to concern for his health and well being.<ref name="soldangels" />  He has raised more than $134,000 toward his cause through donations and sponsorships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drumhike.com/location/track-me-now/|title=Location|publisher=Drumhike.com|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref> he soon picked up sponsorship from [[Wish Upon A Hero|Wish upon A Hero Foundation]] and finished the remaining 2500 miles all the way to the east coast and back home to Louisville KY. In the final 6 months of the Hike for Heroes Troy Yocum raised another $1.1 million. 

On May 26, 2011, Yocum was welcomed to [[Washington, DC]] by [[Congressman]] [[John Yarmuth]] (D-KY) accompanied by firefighters, veterans, and a police escort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yarmuth.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=14&sectiontree=3,14&itemid=814|title=Yarmuth Welcomes "Hike for Heroes" To United States Capitol Building|date=26 May 2011|accessdate=31 May 2011|publisher=House.gov|location=Washington, DC}}</ref>

Yocum completed his 7,880 mi. walk on Sept. 3, 2011.<ref name = "facebookwalkannouncement">{{Cite web
| title = Iraq War veteran Troy Yocum walks 7880 miles across America and raises $1.1 Million for Military families in need! | Facebook
| accessdate = 2011-09-21
| url = http://www.facebook.com/notes/hike-for-our-heroes/iraq-war-veteran-troy-yocum-walks-7880-miles-across-america-and-raises-11-millio/10150282039257455
}}</ref>

==Personal life==
A native of [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], [[Kentucky]], Yocum met his wife Mareike in [[Germany]]. He proposed marriage to her on the 100th mile of the hike, and they were married at mile 256.<ref name="foxnews">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2011/05/28/army-vet-hikes-american-raise-money-fellow-vets/?test=latestnews|title=U.S. Army Vet Hikes Across America to Raise Money for Fellow Vets|date=28 May 2011|accessdate=28 May 2011|work=Fox News}}</ref> She walked over 4,000 miles with him during the course of the walk. Yocum was also accompanied by his [[Shiba Inu]] dog, Emmie.<ref name = "facebookwalkannouncement" />

==Military career==
Yocum graduated in 1997 from [[Trinity High School (Louisville)|Trinity High School]] in  [[St. Matthews, Kentucky|St. Matthews]], Kentucky, and spent two years in the [[Army National Guard]] with the 151st Infantry of southern [[Indiana]].<ref name="tonic">{{cite web|url=http://www.tonic.com/people/troy-yocum/|title=Troy Yocum|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>

==Attempts drumming world record==
In April 2009, Yocum attempted to beat the world record of 120 hours of marathon drumming set by Russ Prager in March 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/Search/Details/Longest-marathon-drumming-by-an-individual/54674.htm|title=Longest marathon drumming by an individual|accessdate=28 May 2011|publisher=Guinness World Records}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/rhythm/soldier-attempts-drumming-world-record-247297|title=Soldier attempts drumming world record|author=Chris Barnes|date=29 April 2009|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref> He was supported by his unit commander and the [[USO]]. In order to beat the record, he had to play for 120 hours in a row with only a five minute break every hour and without repeating any songs for four hours and thirty minutes.<ref name="tonic">{{cite web|url=http://www.tonic.com/people/troy-yocum/|title=Troy Yocum|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref> He attempted to play 250 songs from the 1950s to modern styles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drummerszone.com/news/newsItem.php?n01ID=6861&type=C|title=Troy Yocum wants to set new world record|date=16 March 2009|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>  He was forced to give up on the second day of the attempt after temperatures reached more than 100 degrees.<ref name="tonic" />

